    lesser = lesser.next;
    return lesser;

As `less` could have been `lesser` and `great` be `greater` the order of rewiring the links is important.

You might have opted for

    ListNode left = null;
    ListNode leftTail = null;
    ListNode right = null;
    ListNode rightTail = null;

    while (head != null) {
        if (head.val &lt; x) {
            if (left == null) {
                left = head;
            } else {
                leftTail.next = head;
            }
            leftTail = head;
        } else {
            if (right == null) {
                right = head;
            } else {
                rightTail.next = head;
            }
            rightTail = head;
        }
        head = head.next;
    }
    if (rightTail != null) {
        rightTail.next = null;
    }
    if (leftTail != null) {
        leftTail.next = right;
    } else {
        left = right;
    }
    return left;

The above one should have seen (at least once), where the LHS variable stems from a condition, the RHS being the same value.
In a language like C one would use this style, with _aliases_.

