Consider that for any repeated values, `(e.g.1,1,1,1,1)` the count of subarrays is `1,3,6,10` for `(1,1),(1,1,1),(1,1,1,1), and (1,1,1,1,1)` respectively.  Notice the deltas between the consecutive terms for the pattern are `2,3,and 4`.  Those deltas increment by `1` so the solution for the `nth` value is `n*(n-1)/2`. Where `n = 1` initially.

To compute that solution in a loop for `5 of the same value` do it as follows;
```
int delta = 0;
int res = 0;
for (int n = 0; n &lt; 5; n++) {
   res = res + delta;
   delta++;
}
System.out.println(res);
```
prints
```
10
```
This is exactly what your loop is doing. But I am changing `count[]` to `delta[]` since it more describes what that array contains.
- the array is initialized to `101` to access deltas for values from `0 to 100` inclusive.  By default deltas are all `0`.  They are considered the initial deltas for all possible values.
- Then as you iterate them you are do the following.
-  `res += delta[a]++;`  Where `a` is used as an index into it&#39;s own delta array to sum the good pairs.  It is first used as `0` since one value does not constitute a pair. It them bumps the delta by `1` for the next occurrence of the same value of `a`.

So here is a more verbose solution which does the same thing as yours.
```
public static int numIdenticalPairs(int[] A) {
     int res = 0;
     int[] deltas = new int[101];
     for (int i = 0; i &lt; A.length; i++) {
         int value = A[i];          // get the value from the array
         int delta = deltas[value]; // get current delta for that value
         res += delta;              // adjust the pair count for all values
         deltas[value] = delta + 1; // increment delta for next occurrence of value.
     }
     return res;
}
```

