No, you can&#39;t implement an interface as the instance level, only the class level. The accepted solution to this problem is called the [adapter pattern](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adapter_pattern).

Assume we have this pre-existing class that doesn&#39;t know about our special interface.

```
public class SomeClass {

  public void doTheThing() {
    ...
  }

}
```

Then we want it to implement a new interface we just came up with.

```
public interface CanDoTheThing {
  public void doTheThing();
}
```

Then we make a wrapper class that *contains* an instance of `SomeClass` and calls the right method.

```
public class SomeClassAdapter implements CanDoTheThing {
  private SomeClass impl;

  public SomeClassAdapter(SomeClass impl) {
    this.impl = impl;
  }

  @Override
  public void doTheThing() {
    this.impl.doTheThing();
  }

}
```

Now when we want to pass an instance `someInstance` of `SomeClass` to a function that needs an instance of `CanDoTheThing`, we instead pass `new SomeClassAdapter(someInstance)`.

It seems like you&#39;re looking for a way to have a class that extends another class while also implementing certain interfaces, without explicitly creating a new subclass for each combination of the base class and interfaces. However, in most programming languages, including Java, you cannot directly achieve this without creating specific subclasses or modifying the class hierarchy.

In your example, if you want both instanceOfB and instanceOfBUsingX to be of the same class type and have B as their base class, while also implementing interface X in the second case, you would typically need to create a class that extends B and implements X. Here&#39;s an example in Java:

    class B implements X { }
    class BUsingX extends B implements X { }
    B instanceOfB = new B();
    BUsingX instanceOfBUsingX = new BUsingX();

This way, you would indeed need to create a separate subclass for each combination of base class and interface.

Alternatively, you could consider using composition instead of inheritance. Instead of directly extending B, you could create a wrapper class that implements the required interface and internally holds an instance of B. This can help you achieve similar behavior without creating numerous subclasses:

    class BWrapper implements X {
    private B wrappedInstance = new B();
    // Implement methods from interface X by delegating to wrappedInstance
    }
    BWrapper instanceOfBUsingX = new BWrapper();

